ce:section.ce:para:
The assay performance of the nanoprobes was evaluated by detecting the CEA in different concentrations. The CEA detection was carried out under the optimal conditions. There is a positive correlation between FL intensity and CEA concentration (Fig. 5
                        a). Taking logarithm of CEA concentration in the range of 1 fg mL−1 to 10 ng mL−1, the FL intensity has a good linear relationship with it (Fig. 5b). The correlation coefficient (R2) is 0.999. The limit of detection (LOD) is calculated to be 794.6 ag mL−1 (based on 3Sb/m criterion). The Sb is the standard deviation of the blank sample and m is the slope of the linearity. The IRA signal response was also read out for quantitative CEA detection. Fig. 5c reveals that the IR absorbance also increases gradually with CEA concentration rising. The IR absorbance at 1099 cm−1 was linearly fitted with the logarithm of CEA concentration ranging from 2 pg mL−1 to 200 ng mL−1 with the correlation coefficient of 0.994 (Fig. 5d). It indicated a good linearity of the calibration curve. The LOD of IRA signal was 1.9 pg mL−1, as also determined by the equation of linear regression and the 3Sb/m criterion. The complementarity of dual readout signals shows great adaptability in the detection of cancer biomarker with wide range and low abundance. The assay performance of the nanoprobes is superior to that of the reported works in recent years (Table 1
                        ).
